That same study goes on to say that one-fifteenth of women in Mozambique report having an abortion when asked, but a quarter of them have had an abortion at some time.

How can four-fifths of those who have had an abortion say it’s “morally wrong” unless you are asking people what they think they should say or else trying to convey the views more traditional people than their own?

What the statistics show is that some people desperately want to be able to use condoms and other methods of contraceptions, but somehow can’t get their hands on them and instead resort to trying to solve the problem “the African way”, meaning that they turn to abortion.

HIV

Professor Yirka makes much of the fact that HIV is on the decline. What he doesn’t tell you is that before he tried to frame these results in this generous way he was able to basically hide that decline from science.

Prior to his own publication on the topic he wrote a paper in which he cited his Brookings Institute colleagues who argued that “The decline in body weight and the mortality, along with other studies, show clearly that the HIV/AIDS epidemic in Mozambique has been massive.”
